{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18587"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18587"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11319"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79941"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11319"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65237"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10395"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26233"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79941"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman participates in an electroencephalogram (EEG) study. The researcher asks her to sit quietly in a dimly lit room with her eyes closed while remaining awake.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the predominant brain wave pattern that would be recorded?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delta waves at 0.5-4 Hz","Theta waves at 4-8 Hz","Gamma waves above 30 Hz","Alpha waves at 8-13 Hz","Beta waves at 14-30 Hz"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe predominant brain wave pattern in this scenario would be \u003Cstrong\u003Ealpha waves at 8-13 Hz\u003C/strong\u003E. Alpha waves are characteristic of relaxed wakefulness when a person\u0027s eyes are closed. They originate primarily from the occipital lobe and are immediately suppressed when the eyes open or when mental activity increases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta waves at 14-30 Hz\u003C/strong\u003E - These occur during active thinking, focus, and problem-solving\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelta waves at 0.5-4 Hz\u003C/strong\u003E - These are seen during deep sleep\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma waves above 30 Hz\u003C/strong\u003E - These are associated with intense cognitive processing and perception\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETheta waves at 4-8 Hz\u003C/strong\u003E - These occur during light sleep and drowsiness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlpha waves are considered a marker of cortical idling - a state where the brain is awake but not actively processing sensory input or engaging in cognitive tasks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alpha waves are rhythmic brain activity of 8-13 Hz recorded on electroencephalogram when a person is awake but relaxed with eyes closed.","Alpha waves originate primarily from the occipital lobe and are most prominent during relaxed wakefulness.","Alpha waves are suppressed when eyes open or during mental activity requiring attention and concentration."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65237"}},"question":{"da